<div id="review_3132780683" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3132780683" />
    <a title="Mari" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7013001-mari"><img alt="Mari" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1570550600p2/7013001.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3132780683?book_show_action=true">Jan 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mari" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mari" href="/user/show/7013001-mari">Mari</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7013001-mari?shelf=2020">2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7013001-mari?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3132780683" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9640952317223588702"><br/>Reading this felt especially poignant at the very start of an election year, in the middle of an impeachment and growing tensions in Iran. Coates has a wonderful essay style and this collection does something that I love: add material and context and a through line for the collection. I loved hearing from Coates about what inspired each piece, what he was trying to get at and his own views of where he succeeded and where he failed. I also enjoyed the conceit of one essay for each year Obama was </span>
  <span id="freeText9640952317223588702" style="display:none"><br />Reading this felt especially poignant at the very start of an election year, in the middle of an impeachment and growing tensions in Iran. Coates has a wonderful essay style and this collection does something that I love: add material and context and a through line for the collection. I loved hearing from Coates about what inspired each piece, what he was trying to get at and his own views of where he succeeded and where he failed. I also enjoyed the conceit of one essay for each year Obama was President. <br /><br />Read straight through, I can definitely see how the topics and themes of each essay might feel repetitive, which is why I think this doesn't quite make it to five stars. I would recommend reading an essay a day, or something similar, to truly enjoy and digest each piece. <br /><br />There is something a little pessimistic about these essays, but in a way that is grounded in, you know, history and realism. It came be tough to consume for that fact, but I feel better for the things I learned and the conclusions I came to because of Coates's work. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9640952317223588702" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


